			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				As a manufacturer, working with walmart is a devil's bargain. You are required to continually lower prices (even if those prices don't make it to the end consumer like the advertising claims) to the point that you must either move your manufacturing offshore or go out of business. Frequently, both happen. If you complain, publically or not, your company gets blacklisted. It looks like a good idea to the marketing people, to become a supplier to walmart. Many companies regret it due to large infrastructure expenses (for example, having to build a walmart-compliant EDI system usually runs in the upper 6 digits to low 8 digits). Frequently, making the jumbo size products that are demanded canibalizes other sales. So what looks like selling more product, is really taking away from your other sales.
<br />

<br />
As an employee, walmarts wages are quite low. About 15% of the hourly employees qualify for food stamps. Managers make over $100k per year while the hourly get by with under $16k. If you can afford the healthcare coverage, your annual deductable will be near $3k.
<br />

<br />
As a competitor, it is hard to compete with walmart, since 15% of their employees qualify for/are getting welfare. It is also hard to compete with a company selling product for prices lower than your wholesale price.
<br />

<br />
As a neighbor, walmart claims that they will not move into cities and towns that do not want them. The actual fact is that they sue the heck out of anyone and everyone that tells them they are unwanted. Look for a ballot initiative in california that makes zoning laws (which would prevent walmart from moving into a town) unconstitutional. Many cities with zoning laws that don't permit big box stores end up changing those laws because they can no longer afford the cost of litigation involving walmart. In other lawsuits, expect them to be very viscious. Remember the bit about Tinkywinky, the purple teletubby, being homosexual? That started when walmart was selling counterfeit teletubbies, and was getting sued by the owners of the teletubbies. The rumors and propaganda about the purple teletubby stopped when walmart lost the suit, lost the appeal and had to remove and destroy the fakes.
<br />

<br />
As a customer, the prices look great. Until you remember that part of your income taxes go to pay the wages of the folks at that store. Yes, you are paying for the welfare checks. There ain't no free lunch.
<br />

<br />
Walmart looks good on paper. But when you do the numbers, walmart is bad for America. Walmart is only good for people who get benefits from cheap labor. They aren't the only cause of the problem, they aren't driving the problem, but they are the biggest part of it and the poster child for the trend destroying America. Expect a new pejorative to become common: <span style="font-style: italic">cheap-labor conservative</span>. I don't think its a conservative movement, but the primary beneficiaries and proponents tend to be conservative.
<br />

<br />
If the walmartization of America continues, expect the US to turn into something resembling Mexico: where the poor majority have nothing, and the aristocrats have it all. The middle class will vanish, leaving only the aristocrats and the serfs. Don't forget, the rich will get their taxes cut, so the poor will be paying for it all. Last time I looked at a Forbes list of the world's richest people, 20 of the top 200 were Mexicans. There is a lot of wealth in that country, but it is highly concentrated in the hands of a few people. Concentrating wealth in a country leads to a lot of instability.
<br />

<br />
The wealth of a country comes from replacing imports with exports (I recommend some economic books by Jane Jacobs). If you stop exporting goods, and only import them, your nation can only decline. Shipping manufacturing overseas was the worst thing that US companies could have done since the 1960s. Offshoring is only the latest part of removing the wealth production of America. If it had been done by outsiders, we would have dropped nukes on them. Instead we sit around having a circle jerk and pretend the good times will last forever. Part of the reason the US economy hasn't fallen into the crapper with, say Thailand, is due to the requirement by OPEC for oil payments to be in dollars. If they had switched to euros, like Sadam Hussein was rumored to be about to do, the dollar will collapse inside a year. And the US will be in the same economic situation as the Soviet Union was in the 1990s. I don't have any great hope of turning this trend around: too many people profit from the existing suffering that is going on. Better buy a couple guns to protect yourself and your family in the coming crash. Fiat money will probably become worthless as well when that happens.
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-walmart23nov23a,1,7637894.story?coll=la-home-headlines" target="_blank" class="postlink">LA times story, part 1 of 3</a> (will need to register for it).
<br />
<a href="http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-walmart24nov24,1,3188309.story?coll=la-home-headlines" target="_blank" class="postlink">Part 2 of 3</a>
<br />
<a href="http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-walmart25nov25,1,3647063.story?coll=la-home-headlines" target="_blank" class="postlink">Part 3 of 3</a><br />
