				<div class="postbody">
				When it comes to drugs and household cleaning/including toiletry/shower items Walmart sets the curve in those markets.  But inventory present at others stores will probably never vanish because there will always be people grabbing something last minute in desperation to not make another stop, and paying a premium for it in the process.  I see people buying laundry detergent in the grocery store and I just think "moron" but I know some just don't want to make another stop.....cleaning agents and pet food items are the big offenders of being way overpriced at grocery stores.
<br />

<br />
Some of us may think of home depot, barnes and noble, and walgreens as our corner stores now, they aren't either.  Walgreens is the closest one (and among the highest price for their inventory).  The thing that has definately died is the corner drug store, with a little bit of everything, sort of a pint sized Walmart if you will.  Walgreens being the last standing, thriving example of this. 
<br />

<br />
In place of that there is larger specialty stores like home depot(EXPO)/Lowes, Barnes and Noble, Dee Ann's/@#%$ (fabric and crafting), Best Buy, Mall shops for clothes, furniture stores of various names.  Home decor like Pier 1, outdoor/gaming/camping equipment stores.....really in these categories, if you settle for what was at Walmart, you may have bought an inferior product.
<br />

<br />
Then there's grocery, Walmart does have good prices for grocery, but they don't always have the best selection or full selection.  People will continue to rely on independent grocery chains and stores for food.
<br />

<br />
Really excluding household cleaning/toiletry/personal hygiene/medicine OTC.   Walmart has lots of competition that will not be crushed by Walmart's low prices.  The specialty shop did not die in essence, it changed form to a larger store which can compete with a conglomerate like Walmart.
<br />

<br />
And Walmart doesn't carry <span style="font-weight: bold"><span style="font-style: italic">everything</span></span>
<br />
Comparing Home Depot to Walmart's home repair/improvement section is hardly a comparison.  Same goes for Best buy and Walmart's electronic section.
<br />
I'm sure Walmart's big sales is the "daily life stuff" and their cheap clothing.
<br />

<br />

<br />
